diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.reason: SLE can manifest with a wide range of symptoms including arthritis, rashes, and autoimmune hemolysis. Lupus can also cause pericarditis and skin manifestations that may resemble psoriaform rash.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA)
diagnoses.reason: Although RA is primarily known for causing joint inflammation, it can have systemic features including skin manifestations such as rheumatoid nodules or psoriaform rash, and pericarditis.

diagnoses.name: Psoriatic Arthritis
diagnoses.reason: This type of arthritis occurs in some who have psoriasis, a condition that features red patches of skin topped with silvery scales. Joint pain and skin rash, as well as nail changes, are common features.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.reason: Characterized by a distinctive skin rash and muscle weakness. The rash can be psoriasiform, and the condition has been linked with other autoimmune phenomena.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.reason: An autoimmune disease that can affect exocrine glands and other tissues, leading to dry skin which can sometimes become thickened or present follicular hyperkeratosis. It may have associated arthropathy.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.reason: MCTD features signs and symptoms of a combination of disorders including SLE, scleroderma, and polymyositis. This includes rheumatic heart disease, which may lead to pericarditis, and skin manifestations.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Hemolytic Anemia (AIHA)
diagnoses.reason: While not a diagnosis that explains all symptoms, AIHA is a potential part of the picture, especially when considering a systemic autoimmune disorder that may present with hemolysis and other rheumatological manifestations.

diagnoses.name: Adult-Onset Still's Disease
diagnoses.reason: This inflammatory condition presents with fever, rash, and joint pain. It can lead to a range of complications including pericarditis and other organ involvement.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.reason: Although primarily a cancer of the lymphatic system, lymphoma can present with systemic symptoms including skin rashes, joint pain, and auto-immune phenomena including hemolysis.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.reason: This disease involves the growth of tiny collections of inflammatory cells in different parts of the body, including the skin, joints, and potentially affecting the heart's pericardium.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE can affect multiple systems including the skin, kidneys, and joints, leading to symptoms such as arthropathy, proteinuria, and fever. Neuropsychiatric lupus can manifest as delirium, and serositis can cause pericardial effusions.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA) with systemic involvement
diagnoses.rationale: While primarily affecting joints (arthropathy), RA can have systemic features including fever and, less frequently, pericardial effusion. Renal involvement is unusual but can present with proteinuria; neurological manifestations, while rare, could explain delirium.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Endocarditis
diagnoses.rationale: It can result in fever, and the heart valve infection might extend to involve the pericardium, leading to pericardial effusion. Embolic phenomena could potentially cause delirium through cerebral emboli. The immune response might trigger arthropathy and proteinuria.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.rationale: MCTD combines features of various systemic autoimmune diseases and can present with arthropathy, fever, proteinuria (due to kidney involvement), and neuropsychiatric symptoms like delirium. MCTD may also lead to pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.rationale: Sarcoidosis is a multisystem inflammatory disease that can present with fever, proteinuria (from kidney involvement), arthropathy, and pericardial effusion. Neurosarcoidosis, though rare, could potentially lead to delirium.

diagnoses.name: Viral Infection (e.g., HIV, COVID-19)
diagnoses.rationale: Certain viral infections can cause a wide range of symptoms including fever, delirium (due to encephalopathy), pericardial effusion, arthropathy (joint pains), and kidney damage manifesting as proteinuria.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This tick-borne illness can result in arthropathy, fever, and, in later stages, neurological symptoms including delirium. Rarely, it might involve the heart leading to pericardial effusion. Proteinuria could reflect secondary kidney involvement.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis (TB)
diagnoses.rationale: TB is a multisystemic infectious disease that can cause fever, proteinuria (from kidney involvement), arthropathy (reactive arthritis), and pericardial effusion (in pericardial TB). TB affecting the brain or meninges could potentially lead to delirium.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis (e.g., Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis)
diagnoses.rationale: This class of diseases involves inflammation of blood vessels, which could cause arthropathy, fever, and proteinuria (from kidney involvement). It is less commonly associated with heart and neurological involvement leading to pericardial effusion and delirium.

diagnoses.name: Whipple's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: A rare bacterial infection that can affect multiple systems, causing symptoms such as fever, arthropathy, and proteinuria. Neurological involvement could potentially lead to delirium. While pericardial effusion is rare, systemic spread can affect any organ.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE is a chronic autoimmune disease that can affect various organs and tissues of the body, causing a wide range of symptoms including arthropathy, nephritis, seizures, synovitis, and pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: Rheumatoid Arthritis primarily causes inflammation of the joints (arthropathy) but can also lead to systemic manifestations such as pericardial effusion and synovitis. Seizures and nephritis are less common but can occur, especially in severe cases.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This disease combines features of multiple autoimmune disorders, including those of the joints, skin, and muscles, as well as potential involvement of the kidneys (nephritis) and heart (pericardial effusion). Seizures can occur, albeit less commonly.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Primarily known for causing dry eyes and mouth, Sjögren's can also lead to joint problems (arthropathy), kidney issues (nephritis), and has been associated with nervous system manifestations, including seizures.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.rationale: Sarcoidosis is characterized by the growth of tiny inflammatory cells in different parts of the body, including the joints (arthropathy), kidneys (nephritis), and heart (pericardial effusion). Neurosarcoidosis can result in seizures.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.rationale: This group of disorders causes inflammation of blood vessels, which can lead to a wide range of symptoms, including joint pain (arthropathy), kidney inflammation (nephritis), and, in rare cases, seizures and pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Caused by Borrelia burgdorferi and transmitted through tick bites, Lyme disease can cause arthritis (especially in the knees), myocarditis or pericarditis (which can manifest as pericardial effusion), neurological disorders (which might include seizures), and, rarely, nephritis.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout the body. Symptoms can include arthritis (arthropathy), kidney inflammation (nephritis), and, while rare, neurological symptoms including seizures. Pericardial effusion is less common but possible.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.rationale: An inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and skin rash. It's associated with inflammatory joint disease (arthropathy) and can have complications involving the kidneys (nephritis) and heart (pericardial effusion). Neurological complications like seizures are unusual but not unheard of.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma)
diagnoses.rationale: An autoimmune disease leading to hardening and tightening of the skin and connective tissues. It can cause complications in the kidneys (nephritis), heart (pericardial effusion), and joints (arthropathy). Seizures are not typically a direct symptom but can occur secondary to other complications.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome

diagnoses.name: Depression

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders

diagnoses.name: Irritable Bowel Syndrome (IBS)
diagnoses.description: An intestinal disorder causing pain in the belly, gas, diarrhea, and constipation. It can also lead to mood swings and is associated with malabsorption in some cases.

diagnoses.name: Bipolar Disorder
diagnoses.description: A disorder associated with episodes of mood swings ranging from depressive lows to manic highs. The mood lability symptom is a hallmark of this condition.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An immune system disorder characterized by dry eyes and mouth. It is associated with systemic symptoms including joint pain, skin rashes, and dental issues like periodontal disease.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS

diagnoses.name: Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS)

diagnoses.name: Eating Disorders

diagnoses.name: Connective Tissue Disorders
diagnoses.description: Diseases like Lupus can cause a wide array of symptoms including lymphadenopathy, abnormal electrolytes, and pulmonary symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: Can cause gastroparesis, abnormal electrolytes, and a host of other symptoms due to the body's inability to properly filter waste.

diagnoses.name: Viral Upper Respiratory Infection
diagnoses.details: Commonly known as the common cold, it can cause laryngitis, lymphadenitis, and general malaise, which might contribute to difficulty concentrating.

diagnoses.name: Influenza
diagnoses.details: Also known as the flu, it can present with upper respiratory symptoms, generalized body aches, and sometimes dysgeusia as a result of systemic symptoms or treatments.

diagnoses.name: COVID-19
diagnoses.details: Caused by the SARS-CoV-2 virus, COVID-19 symptoms range from mild to severe respiratory illness, including laryngitis, lymphadenitis, chest pain, difficulty concentrating, and dysgeusia.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.details: While primarily known for causing heartburn, GERD can also lead to chest pain, laryngitis due to acid reflux, and potentially dysgeusia.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.details: Chronic anxiety can manifest physically with symptoms like chest pain and difficulty concentrating, and stress can exacerbate dysgeusia.

diagnoses.name: Mononucleosis
diagnoses.details: Caused by the Epstein-Barr virus, it can cause significant lymphadenitis, fatigue (contributing to difficulty concentrating), chest pain, and sometimes laryngitis.

diagnoses.name: Mycoplasma Pneumoniae Infection
diagnoses.details: A type of atypical bacterial pneumonia that can cause chest pain, lymphadenitis, and can sometimes lead to dysgeusia or taste disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Strep Throat
diagnoses.details: Caused by the bacterium Streptococcus pyogenes, it can present with laryngitis, lymphadenitis, and in some cases, chest pain if there's an associated peritonsillar abscess.

diagnoses.name: Acute Bronchitis
diagnoses.details: An infection of the airways that can cause cough, chest pain, and sometimes laryngitis and lymphadenitis. The associated fatigue may impact concentration.

diagnoses.name: Zinc Deficiency
diagnoses.details: This can manifest with dysgeusia and general malaise, including difficulty in concentrating. Less directly, it can influence the immune response, potentially exacerbating conditions like laryngitis and lymphadenitis.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune thyroiditis (Hashimoto's thyroiditis)
diagnoses.reasoning: Commonly presents with hypothyroidism which can explain the palpitations (due to compensatory mechanisms) and difficulty focusing vision. Also associated with other autoimmune disorders that could potentially lead to liver enzyme abnormalities.

diagnoses.name: Hyperthyroidism
diagnoses.reasoning: Though primarily known for causing hyperactivity of the thyroid, hyperthyroidism can lead to osteopenia due to accelerated bone turnover, palpitations due to increased cardiac output, and eye symptoms including difficulty focusing. Fluctuating thyroid function can also transiently affect liver enzyme levels.

diagnoses.name: Primary biliary cholangitis
diagnoses.reasoning: A chronic liver disease that can lead to abnormal liver enzymes. It's associated with other autoimmune conditions such as thyroid disorders, which could account for the hypothyroidism.

diagnoses.name: Graves' disease
diagnoses.reasoning: An autoimmune disorder leading to hyperthyroidism might cause palpitations and eye symptoms including difficulty in focusing vision. Hyperthyroidism also contributes to osteopenia and could have indirect effects on liver enzymes.

diagnoses.name: Hepatitis
diagnoses.reasoning: While primarily affecting the liver and causing abnormal liver enzymes, chronic hepatitis can be associated with extrahepatic manifestations such as thyroiditis.

diagnoses.name: Alcohol-related liver disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Can lead to abnormal liver enzymes and osteopenia due to poor nutrition and vitamin deficiencies. Alcohol can also exacerbate or contribute to thyroid dysfunctions.

diagnoses.name: Celiac disease
diagnoses.reasoning: An autoimmune disorder that can be linked to thyroid disease, affect the liver enzyme levels, and contribute to osteopenia due to malabsorption of calcium and vitamin D.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: An autoimmune disease that often presents with other autoimmune disorders like thyroid disease. It can lead to liver enzyme abnormalities and symptoms like difficulty focusing vision due to dry eyes.

diagnoses.name: Primary hyperparathyroidism
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause osteopenia due to increased bone turnover, palpitations as a result of hypercalcemia, and indirectly affect vision focusing due to calcium deposits. There can also be a distant effect on liver function tests.

diagnoses.name: Wilson's disease
diagnoses.reasoning: A rare inherited disorder that causes copper accumulation, leading to liver dysfunction and abnormal liver enzymes. It can also result in osteopenia and various neurological and psychiatric symptoms, potentially affecting vision focus and thyroid function indirectly.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormones. Can cause delayed puberty, mood swings that might be confused with anxiety, and, in some cases, may contribute to skin and mucous membrane issues.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Polyglandular Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition involving multiple endocrine gland deficiencies. It can manifest with symptoms like delayed puberty due to hormone imbalances, anxiety, and can sometimes lead to hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Stress
diagnoses.description: Protracted stress can lead to a variety of physical and psychological symptoms including anxiety, which can manifest as pseudoseizures, and potentially contribute to immune dysfunction manifesting as hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Conversion Disorder (Functional Neurological Symptom Disorder)
diagnoses.description: A mental condition in which a person has blindness, paralysis, or other nervous system (neurologic) symptoms that cannot be explained by medical evaluation. Symptoms could include pseudoseizures and occurs often alongside anxiety disorders.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where the ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine. It can cause delayed puberty due to malabsorption of nutrients, anxiety, and may cause leukoplakia-like symptoms due to nutrient deficiencies.

diagnoses.name: Turner Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A chromosomal disorder affecting females, where one of the X chromosomes is missing or partially missing. It can lead to delayed puberty, and some individuals may experience mood disorders such as anxiety.

diagnoses.name: Klinefelter Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A genetic condition affecting males, caused by an extra X chromosome. Symptoms can include delayed puberty, and less commonly, mood or affective disorders.

diagnoses.name: Lichen Planus
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory condition that can affect skin and mucosal membranes such as in the mouth, leading to leukoplakia-like lesions. It may also be associated with a higher incidence of psychosomatic symptoms including anxiety.

diagnoses.name: Oral Lichen Planus
diagnoses.description: A chronic condition that causes swelling and inflammation in the mouth, leading to white patches that may resemble leukoplakia. It can be stressful to manage and may exacerbate or correlate with anxiety disorders.

diagnoses.name: Hypogonadism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the body's sex glands produce little or no hormones. It can lead to delayed puberty, and associated psychological or emotional challenges could potentially contribute to anxiety symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Hypersensitivity reactions
diagnoses.description: Reactions due to an exaggerated response of the immune system. They can cause a range of symptoms including angioedema, laryngitis, and irritated eyes.

diagnoses.name: Allergic reactions
diagnoses.description: Allergic reactions can present with basophilia, angioedema, laryngitis, and eye irritation. Seizure can occur in severe cases due to hypoxia or other systemic effects.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic condition that causes recurrent episodes of severe swelling (angioedema), which could be associated with laryngeal edema and potentially life-threatening airway obstruction. It doesn't typically cause seizures directly, but stress or anxiety from the episodes can potentially trigger seizures in predisposed individuals.

diagnoses.name: C1 inhibitor deficiency
diagnoses.description: C1 inhibitor deficiency, including hereditary and acquired forms, can lead to episodes of angioedema, which may sometimes be associated with laryngitis or eye irritation due to swelling in nearby tissues.

diagnoses.name: Drug reactions
diagnoses.description: Certain medications can cause side effects or allergic reactions presenting with basophilia, seizures, angioedema, laryngitis, and irritated eyes.

diagnoses.name: Chronic myeloid leukemia (CML)
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that affects the white blood cells and can cause basophilia. While not directly causing seizure disorders, the systemic effects of CML and its treatment can potentially affect nervous system function.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A central nervous system disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures. While epilepsy itself does not cause basophilia, angioedema, laryngitis or irritated eyes, the stress from seizures can exacerbate allergic reactions or hypersensitivity in predisposed individuals.

diagnoses.name: Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can affect multiple organs and body systems, potentially causing seizure disorders, angioedema, and other symptoms. Basophilia may occur as a response to chronic inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the blood vessels that can cause a wide range of symptoms including seizures, angioedema, and irritation of the eyes. Laryngitis could occur if the vasculitis involves the laryngeal vessels.

diagnoses.name: Mast cell disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions that cause abnormal accumulations of mast cells, which are involved in allergic reactions. Symptoms can include irritation of the eyes, angioedema, and potentially laryngitis. Seizures are less common but could occur due to systemic involvement or as a reaction to high levels of mediators released by mast cells.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: An underactive thyroid can lead to symptoms like fatigue (which could be misinterpreted as hyperactivity due to unrestful sleep), fibrosis (myxedema), and occasionally headaches or angioedema.

diagnoses.name: Idiopathic Hypereosinophilic Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by a high count of eosinophils, a type of blood cell, leading to various symptoms including fibrosis, possibly headaches and hyperactivity depending on the organ systems involved.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can affect many parts of the body, including skin (leading to fibrosis), nervous system (headaches), and can have renal implications that might affect ferritin levels.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine, potentially causing malabsorption which leads to hypoferritinemia. Linked with systemic symptoms including headaches.

diagnoses.name: Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD)
diagnoses.description: A brain disorder marked by an ongoing pattern of inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity that interferes with functioning or development. While ADHD itself doesn't cause the other symptoms, co-existing conditions might.

diagnoses.name: Mast Cell Activation Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition in which mast cells excessively release chemical mediators, potentially leading to symptoms like angioedema, fibrosis over long-term, and may relate to headaches or nutritional deficiencies affecting iron levels.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Hepatitis

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: Epilepsy is a neurological disorder marked by sudden recurrent episodes of sensory disturbance, seizures, or loss of consciousness. Aphasia and sensory disturbances such as visual scotoma can occur during or after a seizure.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: This condition results from reduced blood flow to the back part of the brain, which is supplied by the vertebrobasilar arterial system. Symptoms can include vertigo, double vision, slurred speech, and in severe cases, stroke-like symptoms such as aphasia and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by visual disturbances and other aura symptoms followed by a severe headache, often on one side of the head. It can include symptoms such as aphasia, scotoma, and phonophobia.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A medical condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death. Symptoms can include weakness on one side of the body, aphasia, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a transient ischemic attack is a temporary period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke. It can include weakness, aphasia, and headache, but generally resolves within 24 hours without permanent damage.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: An abnormal growth of cells within the brain that can cause symptoms like headache, weakness, aphasia, and visual disturbances including scotoma.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that affects the brain and spinal cord, leading to weakness, coordination and balance difficulties, and can include symptoms like visual disturbances and aphasia in more advanced cases.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A central nervous system disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness. Specific types can include symptoms such as aphasia and headache.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the membranes (meninges) surrounding your brain and spinal cord, often caused by infection. Symptoms can include headache, weakness, and in severe cases, aphasia due to brain involvement.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A focal collection of pus within the brain caused by an infection, presenting symptoms like headache, neurological deficits such as weakness, and potentially aphasia if areas governing speech are affected.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the brain, caused by an infection or an autoimmune response. Symptoms can include headache, weakness, aphasia, and photophobia.

diagnoses.name: Hemorrhagic Stroke
diagnoses.description: Occurs when a weakened blood vessel ruptures and bleeds into the surrounding brain. Symptoms can include headache, weakness, aphasia, and in some cases, visual disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic, typically progressive disease involving damage to the sheaths of nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord, symptoms may include numbness, impairment of speech and of muscular coordination, blurred vision and severe fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A sudden disabling attack or loss of consciousness caused by an interruption in the flow of blood to the brain, especially through thrombosis.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Many different types of brain tumors exist. Symptoms can include headaches, changes in speech or hearing, imbalance, and numbness or tingling.

diagnoses.name: Myasthenia Gravis
diagnoses.description: A weakness and rapid fatigue of muscles under voluntary control. The condition is caused by a breakdown in communication between nerves and muscles, symptoms include weakness in the arm and leg muscles, double vision, and difficulties with speech and chewing.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barré Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder in which your body's immune system attacks your nerves, leading to muscle weakness and tingling in your extremities. It can eventually lead to paralysis.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition characterized by intense, debilitating headaches. Symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, difficulty speaking, numbness or tingling, and sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)
diagnoses.description: A nervous system disease that weakens muscles and impacts physical function. Symptoms include difficulty walking or talking, muscle weakness, and muscle cramps.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition resulting from restricted blood flow to the back of the brain. Symptoms might include dizziness, double vision, slurred speech, and imbalance.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: A benign tumor on the main nerve leading from the inner ear to the brain. Symptoms may include hearing loss, ringing in one ear, dizziness, and numbness of the face.

diagnoses.name: Peripheral Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: A result of damage to your peripheral nerves, often causes weakness, numbness and pain, usually in your hands and feet. It can also affect other areas and body functions including digestion, urination, and circulation.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition characterized by intense headaches often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light and sound. In some cases, migraines can also cause aura (including scotoma) and temporary hearing loss.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear causing vertigo, hearing loss, ringing in the ear (tinnitus), and sometimes a feeling of fullness or pressure in the ear. Nausea and headaches can also occur.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain. It can lead to symptoms such as headache, nausea, vision problems (including scotoma), and hearing loss, depending on the tumor's location.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: A benign tumor on the cranial nerve that connects the inner ear with the brain. It primarily causes hearing loss and can also lead to tinnitus, headache, nausea, and balance issues.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system) where the immune system attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers, causing communication problems between your brain and the rest of your body. Symptoms can include headache, nausea, and in rare cases, hearing loss and scotoma due to optic nerve involvement.

diagnoses.name: Hypertension (High Blood Pressure)
diagnoses.description: Chronic high blood pressure can lead to headache, nausea, and in severe cases, can cause damage to the blood vessels of the eye (leading to scotoma) and affect hearing.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular Migraine
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine where vertigo is a predominant symptom along with migraine headaches. Patients might experience nausea, vomiting, and hearing loss.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by the Borrelia bacteria, spread by ticks. It can cause a wide range of symptoms, including headache, nausea, potential hearing loss, and neurological manifestations like facial palsy, which could indirectly affect vision.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Inner Ear Disease (AIED)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune condition where the immune system mistakenly attacks the inner ear structures, leading to progressive hearing loss. It can also cause balance issues, tinnitus, and some patients may experience headache and nausea.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, it temporarily blocks blood flow to the brain. It can cause symptoms such as headaches, nausea, and depending on the area of the brain affected, may cause temporary hearing loss or vision changes like scotoma.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: Complex migraine can present with visual disturbances (scintillation), sensory symptoms (paresthesia), and even motor weakness as part of the aura component.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder affecting the brain and spinal cord, causing symptoms like paresthesia, weakness, and could potentially involve auditory symptoms like tinnitus in some cases.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, it can lead to temporary episodes of symptoms such as weakness, paresthesia, and visual disturbances. Tinnitus is less commonly associated but can occur.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A neurological emergency where an area of the brain is deprived of blood flow. Symptoms can include sudden weakness, sensory changes, and in less common cases, auditory changes.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: An inner ear disorder that can cause episodes of vertigo, hearing loss, tinnitus, and a feeling of fullness in the ear.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: Can lead to neurological issues such as paresthesia, weakness, and in some cases, auditory symptoms like tinnitus due to nerve damage.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Depending on its location, a brain tumor could cause a wide range of neurological symptoms, including weakness, sensory changes, auditory symptoms, and visual disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: A benign tumor on the vestibulocochlear nerve can cause tinnitus, hearing loss, and balance issues.

diagnoses.name: Diabetic Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: A complication of diabetes leading to nerve damage, presenting with symptoms like paresthesia and weakness. Tinnitus is less directly associated but can occur in some individuals.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by recurrent attacks of moderate to severe throbbing and pulsating pain on one side of the head. The aura includes visual disturbances and other neurological symptoms that appear before the headache and last for about 20 to 60 minutes.

diagnoses.name: Transient ischemic attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a ministroke, a TIA is a temporary period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke. A TIA usually lasts only a few minutes and doesn't cause permanent damage.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular migraine
diagnoses.description: This condition combines migraine headache and vertigo. Patients experience episodes of vertigo as well as migraine symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells start to die in minutes. Symptoms can include sudden weakness, face drooping, and severe headache.

diagnoses.name: Multiple sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. Symptoms can include fatigue, numbness, weakness, and in some cases, visual disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Brain tumor
diagnoses.description: Any growth of abnormal cells in the brain. Whether malignant (cancerous) or benign (non-cancerous), brain tumors can cause symptoms like headache, seizures, and changes in vision.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear that can lead to dizzy spells (vertigo) and hearing loss. In most cases, Meniere's disease affects only one ear.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar insufficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition resulting from a temporary lack of blood flow to the posterior part of the brain, which can cause symptoms including vertigo, dizziness, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A central nervous system (neurological) disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness.

diagnoses.name: Hypertensive crisis
diagnoses.description: A severe increase in blood pressure that can lead to a stroke. Symptoms may include headache, severe anxiety, nosebleed, and feeling of shortness of breath.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor

diagnoses.name: Migraine

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis

diagnoses.name: Meningitis

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy

diagnoses.name: Hemorrhagic Stroke

diagnoses.name: Stroke

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor

diagnoses.name: Cervical Spondylosis
diagnoses.details: Degeneration of the spine in the neck can lead to numbness and weakness in the arms, and headaches.

diagnoses.name: Diabetic Neuropathy
diagnoses.details: High blood sugar levels in diabetes can cause nerve damage, leading to numbness and weakness. Headache could be indirectly related.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barré Syndrome

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE can present with cutaneous manifestations (i.e., rashes, including annular polycyclic), hematological disorders like hemolytic anemia, renal involvement manifesting as proteinuria, and neurological manifestations including peripheral neuropathy.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: Rheumatoid arthritis can occasionally present with skin rash, anemia of chronic disease (which could be hemolytic in severe cases), renal involvement, and peripheral neuropathy due to vasculitis.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.rationale: This condition is characterized by muscle weakness and skin rash, but can also feature peripheral neuropathy. While hemolytic anemia and proteinuria aren't classic, autoimmune overlap syndromes could present with these findings.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.rationale: MCTD can present with features of SLE, scleroderma, and polymyositis including skin rashes (such as annular polycyclic), hematological issues like hemolytic anemia, renal involvement, and peripheral neuropathy.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: While predominantly affecting salivary and lacrimal glands, Sjögren's syndrome can be associated with extraglandular manifestations like peripheral neuropathy and renal dysfunction, which might include proteinuria. Hemolytic anemia and rash are less common but possible in systemic disease.

diagnoses.name: Polyarteritis Nodosa (PAN)
diagnoses.rationale: PAN is a systemic vasculitis that can cause skin rashes (including those that could be described as annular polycyclic in nature), renal involvement with proteinuria, peripheral neuropathy, and anemia, though hemolytic anemia is less typical.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Advanced Lyme disease can manifest with a variety of symptoms including annular polycyclic rashes (erythema migrans), hemolytic anemia, renal involvement (although proteinuria is uncommon), and peripheral neuropathy.

diagnoses.name: Cryoglobulinemia
diagnoses.rationale: Cryoglobulinemia can lead to skin manifestations like rashes, renal disease that presents as proteinuria, peripheral neuropathy, and hematological abnormalities, including hemolytic anemia, especially in the context of associated conditions like Hepatitis C.

diagnoses.name: Leptospirosis
diagnoses.rationale: This bacterial infection can cause a wide range of symptoms, including rash, hemolytic anemia, kidney damage (with proteinuria), and peripheral neuropathy, especially in severe cases.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.rationale: Various forms of vasculitis (e.g., granulomatosis with polyangiitis, microscopic polyangiitis) can present with cutaneous manifestations, hemolytic anemia, renal involvement like proteinuria, and peripheral neuropathy.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause inflammation and damage to various body tissues, including the skin, joints, kidneys, heart, and lungs.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: A complication of severe, longstanding rheumatoid arthritis, characterized by inflammation of blood vessels, which can affect the skin causing rashes and ulcers.

diagnoses.name: Cryoglobulinemia
diagnoses.description: A condition associated with the presence of cryoglobulins in the blood, which can precipitate at cold temperatures, causing vasculitis, skin manifestations (such as purpura, ulcers), and kidney damage.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and a distinctive skin rash, including Gottron's papules and heliotrope rash. It may sometimes involve internal organs.

diagnoses.name: Henoch-Schonlein Purpura
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of small blood vessels (vasculitis) that causes them to bleed into the skin, intestines, and kidneys. It often presents with a purpuric rash, abdominal pain, and kidney involvement.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: A disease characterized by the growth of granulomas (clusters of inflammatory cells) in various parts of the body, most commonly the lungs and lymph nodes, but skin and other organs can be affected.

diagnoses.name: Atypical Hemolytic Uremic Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare disease characterized by the triad of hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenia, and acute renal failure. It is considered a type of thrombotic microangiopathy.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer of the blood and bone marrow that most commonly affects older adults. It can cause skin manifestations and immune-mediated complications such as hemolytic anemia.

diagnoses.name: Lymphomatoid Granulomatosis
diagnoses.description: A rare, Epstein-Barr virus-associated lymphoproliferative disorder that affects the lungs, skin, kidneys, and central nervous system, often presenting with skin lesions and systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis
diagnoses.description: Formerly known as Wegener's granulomatosis, it is a rare disorder characterized by inflammation of the blood vessels that can affect the nose, lungs, kidneys, and skin, among other organs.
